# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1970-american-league-championship-series
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The **1901 major league baseball season** was contested from April 18 through October 6, 1901.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1901-major-league-baseball-season] It was the inaugural major league season for the American League (AL) (having previously been the minor league Western League), with the Chicago White Stockings winning the AL pennant.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1901-major-league-baseball-season] In the National League (NL), in operation since 1876, the Pittsburgh Pirates won the NL pennant.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season of the modern era.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the only season in which the Milwaukee Brewers played, as the team would relocate to St.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis, Missouri for the following season as the St.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns (before that team relocated to Baltimore, Maryland as the modern Baltimore Orioles in 1954, where they remain to this day.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles of this season would fold following the 1902 season).
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The 1901 schedule consisted of 140 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 20 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This format had previously been used by the National League during their 1888–1891 seasons.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This format would last until 1904, which saw an increase of games played.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1901-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on April 18 with a game between the Brooklyn Superbas and the Philadelphia Phillies, while American League Opening Day did not take place until April 24, with a game between the Chicago White Stockings and the Cleveland Bluebirds.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The American League would see its final day of the season on September 28, while the National League would see its final day of the season on October 6.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1901-major-league-baseball-season] On February 27, 1901, the National League Rules Committee announced several rule changes, effective immediately.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Blue laws restricted Sunday activities in several localities, causing several teams to play at ballparks in a different locality.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1901-major-league-baseball-season] 15 tie games (8 in AL, 7 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Reds would play their final game at League Park, on October 6 during a doubleheader against the St.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals, moving into the Palace of the Fans for the start of the 1902 season.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1901-milwaukee-brewers-season] The **1901 Milwaukee Brewers** were an American professional baseball team.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1901-milwaukee-brewers-season] This was the final season of the Milwaukee Brewers team that operated from 1894 to 1901, one of multiple teams in Milwaukee's professional baseball history to use the Brewers nickname, and the only season the team competed at the major-league level.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1901-milwaukee-brewers-season] The Brewers finished eighth in the inaugural season of the American League with a record of 48 wins and 89 losses, 35+1⁄2 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1901-milwaukee-brewers-season] After the season, the major-league franchise relocated and became the St.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1901-milwaukee-brewers-season] Louis Browns, where they remained through the 1953 season, after which the franchise again relocated and became the Baltimore Orioles.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1901-milwaukee-brewers-season] A franchise in the minor-league American Association played in Milwaukee from 1902 through 1952 using the Milwaukee Brewers name.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1901-milwaukee-brewers-season] 4/25/01: In the first game of the season in Detroit, the Brewers held a 13–4 lead going into the ninth inning.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1901-milwaukee-brewers-season] The Detroit Tigers scored 10 runs in the bottom of the inning to win, a record which still stands as the greatest ninth inning comeback in major league baseball history.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1901-washington-senators-season] The 1901 Washington Senators won 61 games, lost 72, and finished in sixth place in the American League in its first year as a major league team.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1901-washington-senators-season] They were managed by Jim Manning and played home games at the American League Park I.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1902-st-louis-browns-season] Louis Browns season** was the first for the franchise in St.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1902-st-louis-browns-season] The team finished second in the American League with a record of 78 wins and 58 losses.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1902-st-louis-browns-season] The Milwaukee Brewers of the American League decided to relocate to St.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1902-st-louis-browns-season] Ownership chose the name "Browns" on purpose, as the St.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1902-st-louis-browns-season] Louis Browns had won American Association titles from 1885 to 1889.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1902-st-louis-browns-season] That team moved to the National League in 1892, became the Perfectos in 1899, and has been known as the Cardinals since 1900.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1902-st-louis-browns-season] The new Browns quickly tried to align itself with fans by raiding the rival Cardinals.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1902-st-louis-browns-season] A couple of Cardinals players were signed, including slick fielding future Hall of Fame shortstop Bobby Wallace and 1901 National League batting champion outfielder Jesse Burkett.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1902-st-louis-browns-season] While playing as the 1901 Brewers, the team had a record of 48–89 (.350) and finished in eighth place, while the 1902 Browns played to a record of 78–58 (.574) and finished in second place.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1902-washington-senators-season] The **1902 Washington Senators** won 61 games, lost 75, and finished in sixth place in the American League.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1902-washington-senators-season] They were managed by Tom Loftus and played home games at the American League Park I.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1903-st-louis-browns-season] Louis Browns season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1903-st-louis-browns-season] The team finished sixth in the American League with a record of 65 wins and 74 losses, 26½ games behind the Boston Americans.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1903-washington-senators-season] The **1903 Washington Senators** won 43 games, lost 94, and finished in eighth place in the American League.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1903-washington-senators-season] Washington had finished in sixth place in each of the previous two seasons (the first two seasons of the American League's existence).
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1903-washington-senators-season] However, they fell to eighth and last in 1903.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1903-washington-senators-season] Their only star player, Big Ed Delahanty, got drunk and fell off a bridge into Niagara Falls midway through the season.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1903-washington-senators-season] The Senators' pitching had always been bad, and indeed, they would allow the most runs in the AL, but without Delahanty the offense sputtered to a halt.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1903-washington-senators-season] Their collective batting average was .231, bad even for the dead-ball era, and no one drove in more than 49 runs.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] The **1970 American League Championship Series** was a semifinal matchup of the 1970 MLB Postseason between the East Division champion Baltimore Orioles and the West Division champion Minnesota Twins.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] Like the year before, the Orioles swept the Twins three games to none, though unlike the year before, the Orioles went on to win the World Series against the Cincinnati Reds.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] Baltimore only had to use their bullpen once in the series when Dick Hall came on to relieve Mike Cuellar in Game 1.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] Dave McNally and Jim Palmer both pitched complete games in Games 2 and 3.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] The Twins enjoyed the lead only once, a 1–0 edge in Game 1 when César Tovar hit a leadoff single in the first, moved to second on a sacrifice bunt, and scored on Harmon Killebrew's single.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] In the second, Mark Belanger's bases-loaded groundout aided by an error put the Orioles up 2–1.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] The Twins' tied the score in the bottom of the inning on Jim Perry's groundout with runners on first and third, but the Orioles put the game out of reach in the fourth inning, aided by Cuellar's bat and the lusty blasts of a strong wind blowing across Metropolitan Stadium.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] Two singles and Brooks Robinson's sacrifice fly produced one fourth-inning run off Jim Perry, the Twins' 24-game winner, and the Orioles loaded the bases with one out after two more singles.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] The lefthanded-hitting Cuellar, with a .089 batting average and 7 RBIs to show for his season's efforts, then pulled a Perry pitch toward foul territory in right field.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] As the ball passed first base it was patently foul.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] Cuellar himself stood transfixed at the plate, watching the pellet transcribe a high parabola in the direction of the right-field seats.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] As the ball soared into the 29-mile-an-hour current, however, it started drifting toward fair territory.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] By the time he arrived at first base, the wind had worked its devilry against the home forces, depositing the ball over the fence in fair territory, and giving Cuellar a grand slam.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] Then Don Buford cuffed Perry for a knock-out home run and reliever Bill Zepp yielded a left-field round-tripper to southpaw-swinging Boog Powell to complete the seven-run outburst.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] The Twins got a run in the bottom of the inning on Tovar's single with two on.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] Next inning, Killebrew's leadoff home run made it 9–4.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] After a double, walk, and groundout, George Mitterwald's two-run single cut the lead to 9–6 and knock Cueller out of the game.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] Hall, a 40-year-old relief specialist, allowed only one hit in the final 4+2⁄3 innings to pick up the victory.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] The Orioles got one more run in the sixth on Powell's RBI single off of Stan Williams with the run charged to Dick Woodson.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] Dave McNally received the second-game assignment and once again delivered another great pitching performance en route to another O's victory.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] The Orioles handed McNally a four-run cushion.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] Boog Powell doubled home Mark Belanger in the first inning after two leadoff walks, Frank Robinson homered with Belanger aboard in the third and McNally himself singled home Andy Etchebarren in the fourth.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] The Twins nearly erased the lead with two swings of the bat in the bottom half, Harmon Killebrew connecting for a home run after a walk to Leo Cárdenas followed by a Tony Oliva home run.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] Stan Williams, following Tom Hall and Bill Zepp to the mound, blanked Baltimore the next three frames and Ron Perranoski zeroed the visitors in the eighth before the East Division champs soon erupted for another big rally of runs.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] They scored seven runs in the inning to tie the record for most runs scored in the ninth inning of a postseason game, which had been done once before in 1936.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] After a double, single and walk loaded the bases with one out, Boog Powell drove in two runs with a double to left, then Merv Rettenmund drove in another with a single.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] Luis Tiant relieved Perranoski as Brooks Robinson reached on an error that allowed Powell to score before Davey Johnson's three-run home run capped the scoring at 11–3 Orioles.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] McNally pitched a complete game to give the Orioles a 2–0 series lead.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] When the series shifted to Baltimore, Earl Weaver called on his workhouse Jim Palmer to wrap it all up.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] The big righthander, just 10 days short of his 25th birthday and two years removed from an arm ailment that threatened his career, was razor sharp, scattering seven hits.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] In fairness, Palmer was entitled to a shutout.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] A brilliant sun blinded Frank Robinson while he was tracking down César Tovar's fifth-inning fly that fell for a single.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] Cardenas' single produced a run after a triple, but that was all for the Twins.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] A 20-game winner with a 2.71 ERA in regular season, Palmer set a personal career high of 12 strikeouts and issued only three walks.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] He also laced a double and figured prominently in the second-inning Oriole run when his blooper to short center field was misplayed for a two-base error.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] Palmer subsequently scored on Buford's single.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] The Twins starting assignment went to Jim Kaat, a 14-game winner who had been handicapped by late-season arm miseries.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] The Orioles struck first when Don Buford singled to lead off the first, moved to second on a sacrifice bunt, then to third on a fly out before scoring on Boog Powell's single.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] The left-hander departed with two on and none out in the third after yielding six hits.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] Andy Etchebarren's fielder's choice off of Bert Blyleven aided by an error allowed one to score.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] After a force out, Palmer's RBI double and Buford's sacrifice fly made it 5–0 Orioles.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] The Orioles got one more run in the seventh on Davey Johnson's home run off of Jim Perry.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] By that time the trend of the game had been established and three successors, while more effective, were helpless to change the outcome, the Birds cruising to an easy victory and the AL pennant.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] The Orioles played flawless defense in the series, handling 110 total chances (81 putouts, 29 assists) perfectly.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] The Twins quickly fell to the middle of the standing in the American League West for many years following 1970.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] Humphrey Metrodome in 1982 and owner Calvin Griffith sold to the team to Carl Pohlad in the middle of the 1984 season.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] The Twins did not reach the postseason again until 1987, when they upset the Detroit Tigers in the ALCS and St.
[src:1970-american-league-championship-series/1970-american-league-championship-series] Louis Cardinals in the World Series, to win the city's first pro sports championship since the 1953–54 Lakers.
